Rediculously addictive, but not without flaws. Like the previous release, FM2015 tends to be unstable on anything other than windows. I've had limite success with Home Streaming. The interface is a bit clunky, and "workflow" in team management isn't entirely intuitive. That said, I'm enjoying the hell out of 2015. If 1) you know that football doesn't involve touchdowns and helmets 2) you know that a football is round and usually kicked, not egg-shaped and usually thrown 3) you know your 4-3-3 from your 4-2-3-1 from your 3-5-2 from your 4-4-2 diamond 4) teams are built, not bought 5) are masochistic enough to enjoy a management simulation then you will love this edition of the most famous sport management simulation on the planet. You know a game has made it into the public consciousness when a common insult when discussing tactical elements of the real sport is an accusion of being a keyboard manager that only knows Football Manager ;)
